the chain.

It galls me to hear how bored some young people are with self-expression and is therefore a legitimate pass-time that they can burn time in logging on to sites like YouTube and watching pointless videos, yet when an opportunity arises for self-expression such as staging a political protest it is frowned upon.

The recent news items about the violent clash between members of a minority group, against whom no fundamental right to gather is in issue, with police, and demonstrators marching against the Guyana Cricket Board, to my way of thinking are similar in many ways. Where in fact, as in the case of the recent protest against the cricket board, the protesters have a legal right to gather and perform their activities but they embark upon them in such a way that they falsify the purpose for which they are gathering and demonstrate. I think that while the residents of Buxton are seeking to address a wrong that has been perpetrated on them by cricket administrators and others, they could do so in a more suitable way than the way they choose to do so. This led me on though, to the issue of how Guyana’s political class has been conducting itself, because I too feel that some of them, as is the residents of Buxton, could benefit from similar protest, which of late has adopted Mozart’s music as part of its chants and slogans. I would like to address three secondary issues which I think are of considerable consequence. First, for the political class, they continue to live in the past
